defaultDevolution – history and issues  default8. Since the 1990’s the history o
defaultf devolution to local government in England has been one of ‘earned autonomy’  - freedoms and flexibilities granted to individual councils, often on a time limited basis linked to the achievement of targets, identified through negotiation with central gove
defaultrnment departments. Local Public Service Agreements, Local Area Agreements and Total Place pilots under the previous government all followed this pattern, and this approach is currently being replicated in individually negotiated City Deals and Community B
defaultudget pilots – although there is a welcome recognition from the present government of the value of  multi area (e.g. city region/LEP or county wide) agreements. Governments have also made additional powers for 
defaultlocal areas 
defaultdependent on moving to new governa
defaultnce arrangements e.g. changing the committee system for the Leader and Cabinet model under the previous government, the additional powers for areas with directly elected mayors granted under the 2011 Localism Act and additional freedoms and funding for are
defaultas establishing Combined Authorities. 
default9. The December 2013 National Audit Office ‘Funding and Structures for local economic growth’ report (p35) also noted: 
default“Local bodies have had to coordinate a range of individual initiatives with different objectives, 
defaultfunding arrangements, timetables and reporting requirements. Local Interviewees have told us that departments have different approaches to localism and how far they devolve responsibility differs. This makes it difficult for local bodies to be clear about 
defaultthe policy framework within which they operate
default”. 
default10. If Government wish to take full advantage of devolution then dev
defaultolved powers and freedoms need to
default be coherent across departments, universal and not time limited, allowing local leaders and business to m
defaultake and deliver effective long term plans and actions for securing economic growth and sustainability. 
default11. We note and welcome that the December 2013 
defaultautumn
default statement (p85) stated that Government will be: “
defaultworking with departments to give local public ser
defaultvices the same long-term indicative budgets as departments from the next Spending Review
default”. Giving local authorities the power to set balanced budgets over the period of these longer term indicative budgets would not only support long term planning for infr
defaultastructure and economic growth but also stimulate further medium term ‘invest to save’ activity by local services.
