defaultA strategic approach to devolutiondefault30
default. As noted above, much of the history of decentralisation and devolution in England has been uncoordinated, selective and short term. 
default31
default. The Key Cities Group would propose that government act in a corporate and strategic manner by developing a cross gove
defaultrnment menu of 
defaultsignificant 
defaultfunding streams and powers
default that local areas could adopt should they meet local needs or provide local opportunities without the need for long and complex negotiations
default. 
defaultThe long term aim of such a project would be to enable cities
default to be self-financing and able to respond quickly, positively and effectively to long term challenges.
default32
default. For cities these would include the freedoms identified by the Core Cities Group with complimentary powers and devolved funding streams being availabl
defaulte to county and 
defaultlarger 
defaultdistrict councils. 
defaultThis would also support the 
defaultprevious recommendation of the C
defaultommittee for a more formalised 
defaultand balanced 
defaultrelationship between central and local government
default. We believe that this would not only significantly strengthe
defaultn economic growth but also create and empower strong civic leadership whilst reducing costs 
defaultof public services to taxpayers and enabling cities to drive economic growth and improved quality of life for all their residents and the wider nation.
